Also, contrary to what others have written,
memset(array, 0, sizeof(array));

isn't guaranteed to result in null pointers. On some systems, a pointer with all its bits set to 0 might actually be valid. For mainstream systems, that's not the case, but with embedded systems, one never knows. The safe way to set all entries to a null pointer is to either loop over the entries yourself and set them to NULL, or to use an uninitialized static array which you can memcpy() over the array you want to set to NULL. A:

static void* array[1024] = {0};

or, as kmkaplan points out in the comment, just:
static void* array[1024];

although I prefer the first solution just to remind me that it's set to zeros (the compiler shouldn't generate any code for this unless it's brain-dead).

